sciplinary paradigm shifts, the contributing writers of The Restless Anthropologist discuss the ways their earlier and later projects compare on both scholarly and personal levels, describing the circumstances of their choices and the motivations that have emboldened them to proceed, to become novices all over again. In doing so, they question some of the central expectations of their discipline, reimagining the space of the anthropological fieldsite at the heart of their scholarly lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aanthropology, anthropologist, mobility, research, fieldwork, travel, west africa, rain forest, city, urban, greece, rural, sheep herding, activism, rome, bangkok, poverty, andes, adoption, belonging, rootlessness, migration, indonesia, tourism, sociology, graduate students, scholarship, diaspora, home, memory, papua new guinea, fieldsites, nonfiction, profile, biography, science, scientists, career.1 aBruner, Edward M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDominguez, Virginia R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGottlieb, Alma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGottlieb, Alma, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHerzfeld, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLepowsky, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRibeiro, Gustavo Lins, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeligmann, Linda J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStoller, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-20